Rationale:
Imagine we have a sequence of cards X₁, X₂, ..., Xₙ. Each Xᵢ corresponds to either a black card or a red card.

Now, let's imagine that we have another variable Y which checks whether Xᵢ and Xᵢ₋₁ are the same color card. Specifically, if Xᵢ ≠ Xᵢ₋₁ then Yᵢ = 1 otherwise Yᵢ = 0. We mark the case of Xᵢ ≠ Xᵢ₋₁ as 1 because it represents the end of a run and our goal is to find the expected number of runs.

Next we want to find E[Y₁, ..., Yₙ
] = E[Y₁
] + E[Y₂
] + ... + E[Yₙ
]. Since E[Yᵢ
] is 1 when Xᵢ ≠ Xᵢ₋₁ we can express E[Yᵢ
] = P(Xᵢ ≠ Xᵢ₋₁)

The expected number of runs is:

E[N
] = ∑P(Xᵢ ≠ Xᵢ₋₁) + 1

The +1 in the equation above represents the first card that we draw. This card will always be counted as one run because there are no cards that were drawn before it.

E[N
] = ∑ Number of ways Xᵢ ≠ Xᵢ₋₁/Total number of combinations + 1 = 51(26/51) + 1 = 27
